# G√©n√©ration des cercles de corr√©lations
pcs = pca.components_

nb = df_num.columns #num√©ro de variable

def display_circles(pcs, n_comp, pca, axis_ranks, labels=None, label_rotation=0, lims=None):
    """Display correlation circles, one for each factorial plane"""
    
    # Initialise the matplotlib figure
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(18,5))
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3)
    
    # For each factorial plane
    for k, (d1, d2) in enumerate(axis_ranks): 
        if d2 < n_comp:

            # Determine the limits of the chart
            if lims is not None :
                xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax = lims
            elif pcs.shape[1] < 30 :
                xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax = -1, 1, -1, 1
            else :
                xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax = min(pcs[d1,:]), max(pcs[d1,:]), min(pcs[d2,:]), max(pcs[d2,:])

            # Add arrows
            # If there are more than 30 arrows, we do not display the triangle at the end
            if pcs.shape[1] < 30 :
                ax[k].quiver(np.zeros(pcs.shape[1]), np.zeros(pcs.shape[1]), 
                             pcs[d1,:], pcs[d2,:], angles='xy', scale_units='xy', 
                             scale=1, color="saddlebrown", headwidth=6, width=0.004,)
            else:
                lines = [[[0,0],[x,y]] for x,y in pcs[[d1,d2]].T]
                ax.add_collection(LineCollection(lines, axes=ax, alpha=.1, color='black'))
            
            # Display variable names
            if labels is not None:  
                for i,(x, y) in enumerate(pcs[[d1,d2]].T):
                    if x >= xmin and x <= xmax and y >= ymin and y <= ymax :
                        ax[k].text(x, y, labels[i], fontsize='15', ha='center', va='center', 
                                 rotation=label_rotation, color="darkslategrey", alpha=0.6)
            
            #Plot circle
            x=np.linspace(start=-1,stop=1,num=500)
            y_positive=lambda x: np.sqrt(1-x**2) 
            y_negative=lambda x: -np.sqrt(1-x**2)
            ax[k].plot(x,list(map(y_positive, x)), color='peru')
            ax[k].plot(x,list(map(y_negative, x)),color='peru')
    
            #Plot smaller circle
            x=np.linspace(start=-0.5,stop=0.5,num=500)
            y_positive=lambda x: np.sqrt(0.5**2-x**2) 
            y_negative=lambda x: -np.sqrt(0.5**2-x**2)
            ax[k].plot(x,list(map(y_positive, x)), color='tan', alpha=0.7, ls='--')
            ax[k].plot(x,list(map(y_negative, x)),color='tan', alpha=0.7, ls='--')

            #Create broken lines
            x=np.linspace(start=-1,stop=1,num=30)
            ax[k].scatter(x,[0]*len(x), marker='_',color='lightgrey')
            ax[k].scatter([0]*len(x), x, marker='|',color='lightgrey')

            # Label the axes, with the percentage of variance explained
            ax[k].set_xlabel('PC{} ({}%)'.format(d1+1, round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[d1],1)))
            ax[k].set_ylabel('PC{} ({}%)'.format(d2+1, round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[d2],1)))

            ax[k].set_title("Correlation Circle (PC{} and PC{})".format(d1+1, d2+1))

from matplotlib.lines import Line2D

def display_factorial_planes(X_projected, n_comp, pca, axis_ranks, labels=None, alpha=1, illustrative_var=None, legend=None):
    '''Display a scatter plot on a factorial plane, one for each factorial plane'''
    
    colors = {'Asie':'gold', 'Afrique':'coral', 'Europe':'yellowgreen', 'Am√©riques':'mediumaquamarine', 'Oc√©anie':'steelblue'}
    
    # Initialise the matplotlib figure      
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(18,6))
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=1)
        
    # For each factorial plane
    for a, (d1, d2) in enumerate(axis_ranks): 
        if d2 < n_comp:
      
            # Display the points
            if illustrative_var is None:
                ax[a].scatter(variabilite.iloc[:, d1], variabilite.iloc[:, d2], 
                              c=my_data['R√©gion'].map(colors), alpha=alpha, s=150)
            elif illustrative_var == 'KMeans':
                sns.scatterplot(ax=ax[a], x=df_clustered.iloc[:, d1], y=df_clustered.iloc[:, d2], hue= df_clustered['cluster_KMeans'], palette=sns.color_palette("Set1", as_cmap=True))
                ax[a].legend()
                fig.suptitle(f"K-Means : Projection des {X_projected.shape[0]} individus sur les plans factoriels r√©partis en {len(centroid)} centres", fontsize=16)
                
            elif illustrative_var == 'HAC':
                sns.scatterplot(ax=ax[a], x=df_clustered.iloc[:, d1], y=df_clustered.iloc[:, d2], hue= df_clustered['cluster_HAC'],palette=sns.color_palette("Set1", as_cmap=True))
                ax[a].legend()
                fig.suptitle(f"Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering : Projection des {X_projected.shape[0]} individus sur les plans factoriels r√©partis en {len(centroid)} centres", fontsize=16)
                        
            # Display the labels on the points
            if labels is not None:
                for i,(x,y) in enumerate(X_projected[:,[d1,d2]]):
                    ax[a].text(x, y, labels[i], fontsize='8', ha='center',va='center', alpha=0.4, c='grey') 
            
            # add a legend

                fig.legend(title='R√©gion', handles=handles, borderaxespad=0,
                      bbox_to_anchor=(0, 1, 1, 0), loc="lower center",  ncol=5)
            
            # Define the limits of the chart
            boundary = np.max(np.abs(X_projected[:, [d1,d2]])) * 1.1
            ax[a].set_xlim([-boundary,boundary])
            ax[a].set_ylim([-boundary,boundary])
        
            # Display grid lines
            ax[a].plot([-100, 100], [0, 0], color='grey', ls='--')
            ax[a].plot([0, 0], [-100, 100], color='grey', ls='--')

            ax[a].set_xlabel('PC{} ({}%)'.format(d1+1, round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[d1],1)))
            ax[a].set_ylabel('PC{} ({}%)'.format(d2+1, round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[d2],1)))

            ax[a].set_title("Projection of points (on PC{} and PC{})".format(d1+1, d2+1))

# Elbow Method
WCSS = [] # within-cluster sums of squares
for k in range (1,10):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters = k, init = "k-means++", random_state = 10)
    km.fit(X_scaled)
    WCSS.append(km.inertia_)

# Coefficient de Silhouette
silhouette_coefficients = []
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init=10, init='k-means++')
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    score = silhouette_score(X_scaled, kmeans.labels_)
    silhouette_coefficients.append(score)

6. Analyse des résultats et choix des pays¶

Les deux m√©thodes de clustering (K-Means et HAC) offre des clusters quasi identiques dont les centro√Øds disposent relativement des m√™mes coordonn√©es sur les variables du dataset. En revanche le nombre d'individus par cluster diff√©re d'une m√©thode √† l'autre.

Nous souhaitons s√©lectionner des pays qui sont en demande (importation forte) et stables. Avec l'analyse des composantes principales, nous avons identifi√© que la composante PC6 correspondait aux Pays qui importent le plus et qui sont stables : on s√©lectionnera donc le cluster n¬∞0 du K-Means ou le n¬∞3 du HAC.
